</ul>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>origin of speech</b> refers to the more general problem of the <a href="/wiki/Origin_of_language" title="Origin of language">origin of language</a> in the context of the physiological development of the human <a href="/wiki/Speech_organs" class="mw-redirect" title="Speech organs">speech organs</a> such as the <a href="/wiki/Tongue" title="Tongue">tongue</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lip" title="Lip">lips</a> and <a href="/wiki/Place_of_articulation" title="Place of articulation">vocal organs</a> used to produce <a href="/wiki/Phoneme" title="Phoneme">phonological units</a> in <a href="/wiki/Human_universal" class="mw-redirect" title="Human universal">all human languages</a>.</p>
<p></p>
